csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class StepDetection : MonoBehaviour
{
    public Transform playerBounds;
    public float stepHeight = 0.5f;
    public float stepDistance = 1f;
    public float moveSpeed = 5f;

    private void Update()
    {
        // Calculate the position in front of the player
        Vector3 forwardPosition = playerBounds.position + playerBounds.forward * stepDistance;

        // Cast a ray downwards to detect steps
        if (Physics.Raycast(forwardPosition, Vector3.down, out RaycastHit hit, stepHeight))
        {
            // Calculate the target position to move the object
            Vector3 targetPosition = hit.point + Vector3.up * stepHeight;

            // Move the object towards the target position
            transform.position = Vector3.MoveTowards(transform.position, targetPosition, moveSpeed * Time.deltaTime);
        }
    }
}


To use this script, follow these steps:

1. Create a new C# script in your Unity project and name it "StepDetection" (or any other name you prefer).
2. Open the script in your preferred code editor.
3. Copy and paste the above code into the script file.
4. Save the script and go back to the Unity editor.
5. Assign the player's bounds (e.g., a collider or an empty GameObject representing the player's position) to the `playerBounds` variable in the Inspector.
6. Adjust the `stepHeight`, `stepDistance`, and `moveSpeed` variables in the Inspector to fit your game's requirements.
7. Attach the script to the object you want to move when encountering steps.
8. Press the Play button in Unity to see the object move on the y-axis when encountering steps in front of the player.

This script uses a raycast to detect steps in front of the player. If a step is detected within the specified `stepHeight`, the object will move towards the step by adjusting its y-position using `Vector3.MoveTowards`.

