Certainly! Here's an example of a shader that hides internal edges but doesn't hide external ones:

shader
Shader "Custom/InternalEdgeShader"
{
    Properties
    {
        _MainTex ("Texture", 2D) = "white" {}
    }
    SubShader
    {
        Tags { "RenderType"="Opaque" }
        LOD 200

        CGPROGRAM
        #pragma surface surf Lambert

        sampler2D _MainTex;

        struct Input
        {
            float2 uv_MainTex;
        };

        void surf (Input IN, inout SurfaceOutput o)
        {
            // Calculate the normal vector
            float3 normal = UnpackNormal(tex2D(_MainTex, IN.uv_MainTex));

            // Calculate the dot product of the normal and the view direction
            float dotProduct = dot(normal, normalize(_WorldSpaceCameraPos - IN.worldPos));

            // If the dot product is positive, it means the normal is facing towards the camera
            // In that case, set the alpha value to 1 to hide internal edges
            // Otherwise, set the alpha value to 0 to keep external edges visible
            o.Alpha = dotProduct > 0 ? 1 : 0;
        }
        ENDCG
    }
    FallBack "Diffuse"
}


To use this shader, follow these steps:

1. Create a new shader file in your Unity project and name it "InternalEdgeShader" (or any other name you prefer) with the ".shader" extension.
2. Open the shader file in your preferred code editor.
3. Copy and paste the above code into the shader file.
4. Save the shader file and go back to the Unity editor.
5. Create a new material and assign the "InternalEdgeShader" to it.
6. Assign a texture to the "_MainTex" property in the Inspector.
7. Apply the material to the desired objects in your scene.

This shader uses the Lambert lighting model and calculates the dot product between the surface normal and the view direction. If the dot product is positive, it means the normal is facing towards the camera, indicating an internal edge. In that case, the alpha value is set to 1 to hide the internal edge. Otherwise, the alpha value is set to 0 to keep the external edges visible.

